&quot;The Shadows Know&quot;<br>
<br>
From the &quot;Xbox Game Evaluation Lab&quot; is intended to give Xbox gamers a sneak peek at groundbreaking Xbox games currently in development. We will deliver unique content by working with the developers to get approval to share exciting, cutting edge information that you just can't find anywhere else.<br>
<br>
Video games are becoming more like real life every day.  Okay, okay, real life doesn't have real Master Chief-quality combat armor or functional 30-story battle 'Mechs, but thanks to the Xbox, video games do have realistic lighting effects.  This may not sound as exciting as armored suits or walking tanks, but when you're looking to get lost in a game, realistic shadows and reflections can make the difference between total immersion and a slight diversion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://pub98.ezboard.com/bgamingarea87"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.xbox.com/NR/rdonlyres/91D40288-E302-4D43-A474-A667724F8A5B/0/ilmtoejamearl30001.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Take for example, SEGA's ToeJam and Earl III:  Mission to Earth.  The game is due out this fall, but the Xbox Game Evaluation Group here at Microsoft recently had the opportunity to sneak an advance peek. The talented folks at Visual Concepts created an environment where bushes and trees move according to the strength and direction of the wind…and so do their shadows. Shadows fall according to where the sun is overhead, and as El Sol moves across the sky to signify the passage of time, these shadows lengthen and shorten accordingly.<br>
<br>
Now what does all this mean to you? Well, these lighting effects interact with other graphical elements (in this case, groovy aliens and huge, detailed environments) and the result is a world that feels more believable to your eyes. When you see Big Earl pass under the shadow of a tree, your mind knows the shadow should not only fall across the ground, but across Big Earl as well. The power of the Xbox makes this detail possible, and helps immerse you more deeply in the game world.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.xbox.com/NR/rdonlyres/2582380C-7940-4187-B00A-3FAA85FCCB12/0/ilmtoejamearl30002.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
You see, the Xbox uses special pieces of computer code called vertex shaders to realize a vast array of lighting effects. The shaders control the brightness and coloring of the world to make it seem more real. The shaders take their cues from the game software and from the Xbox graphics processor, and then make sure that nighttime scenes look darker and more shadowy than scenes set at high noon. From the pitch-black darkness of a starless night with no moon, to a full moon splendor of a nighttime Fourth of July fireworks show, the vertex shaders can deliver as much or as little light as the game requires.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.xbox.com/NR/rdonlyres/A5C52D31-F158-4AAC-83C9-3B2725B3F9FE/0/ilmtoejamearl30003.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
But pretty pictures aren't the only thing that realistic lighting effects provide. In TJ&amp;E3, the time of day affects game play, too. At night, most regular Earthlings are sleeping and will pose no threat to our funked-up heroes. Night time is the right time for Boogiemen and Ghosts, however, who rise when the sun sets to make your life difficult.<br>
<br>
When you get a chance to play TJ&amp;E3, take a moment to appreciate the lighting effects. They're details, sure, but they're realistic details. In fact, this unique game was designed to use the power of the Xbox to create the most realistic shadows and reflections possible.  Think how pleased the designers will be when you mention that you noticed.<br>
<br>
And in the meantime, enjoy the view.<br>
