Phantasy Island<br>
<br>
<br>
By Ryan McCaffrey, Assistant Editor<br>
<br>
Week of Feb. 19—While it's true that working at the Official Xbox Magazine is one of the coolest jobs on earth … it's still a job. As such, we are forced to do work—work that doesn't involve playing games. (Even we can't try and tell you that merely playing games is a job!) This past week, we've been on deadline. This is the one week per month that actually kinda sucks. We have to write stories, layout pages, fact check, and do other things that don't involve our hands on an Xbox controller. But, luckily, game companies could care less about our deadlines and occasionally stop by to visit, giving us no choice but to sit and play their games. (I know, it's rough … )<br>
<br>
This week, Microsoft stopped by and let us sit down and play a little Phantasy Star Online: Episode I &amp; II and Tao Feng: Fist of the Lotus. If you are familiar with PSO for the Dreamcast, then you'll know exactly what to expect from this game, with one major difference: Xbox Live. No more 56K slowdown and no more annoying typing. PSO on Xbox Live is silky smooth, and the Voice Communicator frees your hands to do more leveling up. The experience is unlike anything currently available for Xbox and certainly has enough depth to satisfy roleplaying fanatics. It's just another example of a game that is made infinitely better solely because of Xbox Live and all that it offers.<br>
<br>
As for Tao Feng, it looks incredible, and the fighting is fast and responsive. John Tobias (the game's creator and co-creator of Mortal Kombat) took us through the impressive stages and showed off the real-time bruising, limb-breaking, and considerable depth of the game. I can honestly say that I've never seen a fighting game look this good … it even looks better than Dead or Alive 3. Once we meet our project deadlines, we're going to sit down and play this game some more, before handing down our final opinion … but right now, it's looking really good.<br>
<br>
We're still playing the heck out of Indiana Jones and the Emperor's Tomb, and you will get to enjoy the fruits of our labor in our April issue (on newsstands March 11, 2003), when we reveal the locations of all 30 artifacts. Oh, and we'll have a cover story on a game you've all been waiting for …<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Livin' Live<br>
We've been playing even more Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon on Xbox Live and recently discovered a semi-hidden gun that is absolutely awesome. The M82A1 is a bit tricky to find, due to the rather obtuse weapon selection in Ghost Recon, but once you pick this bad boy, it is a treat. The best part about this weapon is the insane noise that it makes. Literally everybody on the server was like, &quot;What kind of crazy gun do you have?&quot; Of course, we didn't tell 'em. It's exceptionally loud and ridiculously powerful, and it has good range. In the real world, it is known to take out lightly armored vehicles. In Ghost Recon we mostly use it to take out people's faces.<br>
